description:
Interaction: lichen_l2.c:lichen_l2_enable <-> lichen_l2.c:lora_rx_callback

Bug: In lichen_l2_enable disable path (lines 1140-1145):
  k_mutex_lock(&tx_mutex, K_FOREVER);
  if (k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_MSEC(100)) != 0) {
    LOG_DBG(...reinitializing...);
    k_mutex_init(&rx_mutex);
    k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_FOREVER);
  }

This trylock pattern with 100ms timeout is used to handle the case where RX thread was aborted while holding rx_mutex.

But lora_rx_callback() and lichen_l2_input() use K_FOREVER:
  Line 1656: k_mutex_lock(&rx_mutex, K_FOREVER);

If enable(false) is called while the RX thread is legitimately processing a large frame (SCHC decompression can take time), the 100ms timeout might expire even though the mutex is validly held. Then k_mutex_init() is called on a validly-held mutex, which is UB.

The 100ms is documented as 'timeout in case of aborted thread', but there's no way to distinguish 'aborted holding mutex' from 'legitimately holding mutex for a long time'.

Frame processing time: SCHC decompression of a full 200-byte compressed payload, plus signature verification (EC point multiply ~10ms on M4), plus AES-CCM. On a slow MCU, this could approach or exceed 100ms.

Trigger:
1. RX thread receives a frame
2. RX thread acquires rx_mutex
3. Signature verification starts (computationally intensive)
4. Meanwhile, network stack calls lichen_l2_enable(false)
5. enable() tries tx_mutex (gets it), then rx_mutex with 100ms timeout
6. Signature verification takes >100ms
7. Timeout expires, k_mutex_init() called on held mutex -> UB
